pageContext.claim: “This is the most aggressive and comprehensive effort to confront a foreign virus in modern history.”
pageContext.analysis: There is no such thing as a “foreign virus.” Viruses can emerge anywhere on Earth. The Spanish Flu that emerged in 1918, killing 20 million to 50 million people, is believed to have started in the United States — the first case was reported there — though no one knows for sure, except that it almost certainly did not start in Spain.
